This paper describes a model for multilingual language processing that operates directly on unicode bytes, making it language-agnostic. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses LSTM-based models, which are commonly used in machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also mentions Part-of-Speech tagging and Named Entity Recognition, which are tasks commonly associated with neural networks (cs.NE). Finally, the paper mentions that the models can be used on raw text, which is a common task in computer vision (cs.CV) for tasks such as optical character recognition.
